{
    "definition": {
        "$schema": "https://schema.management.azure.com/providers/Microsoft.Logic/schemas/2016-06-01/workflowdefinition.json#",
        "actions": {
            "HTTP_Request_to_Chrome": {
                "inputs": {
                    "headers": {
                        "Content-Type": "application/json"
                    },
                    "method": "POST", // or GET, PUT, DELETE depending on the requirement
                    "uri": "http://<CHROME_DEBUGGING_ENDPOINT>", // Change to the actual Chrome Debug URL
                    "body": "{ \"method\": \"Page.navigate\", \"params\": { \"url\": \"https://example.com\" } }" // Example payload
                },
                "runAfter": {},
                "type": "Http"
            }
        },
        "triggers": {
            "manualTrigger": {
                "inputs": {},
                "recurrence": {
                    "frequency": "OneTime",
                    "interval": 1
                },
                "type": "Request"
            }
        },
        "contentVersion": "1.0.0.0",
        "outputs": {}
    },
    "parameters": {}
}
```

### Explanation:
1. **Trigger**:
    - `"triggers": { "manualTrigger": { "type": "Request" ... } }`: This defines an HTTP request trigger. The logic app starts when an HTTP request is received.

2. **Action**:
    - `"actions": { "HTTP_Request_to_Chrome": { "type": "Http" ... } }`: This is the action that sends an HTTP request to the Chrome Debugging endpoint.
    - `"method": "POST"`: Defines the HTTP method used (can be changed to GET, PUT, DELETE, as required).
    - `"uri": "http://<CHROME_DEBUGGING_ENDPOINT>"`: Replace this with the actual URL for the Chrome Debugging endpoint.
    - `"headers": { "Content-Type": "application/json" }`: Sets the content type for the request.
    - `"body": "{ \"method\": \"Page.navigate\", \"params\": { \"url\": \"https://example.com\" } }